## Using Function Templates in Multiple Files

When you split a normal function across files, you put the declaration in a header and the definition in a `.cpp` file. Function templates **cannot** follow this pattern without extra work — and the workaround that pattern requires is almost never worth it.

### Why the Usual Approach Breaks

The compiler generates template instantiations (covered in *Function template instantiation*) at compile time, on demand, for each type it encounters. When the template definition lives in a `.cpp` file, it is compiled in isolation — the compiler sees no calls there, so it instantiates nothing. A different translation unit that includes only the declaration then tries to link against an instantiation that was never created, producing an unresolved external symbol error.

### The Standard Solution: Define Templates in Headers

Put the full template definition directly in the header file. Every translation unit that includes the header then has everything it needs to instantiate the template for any required type.

```cpp
// math_utils.hpp
#pragma once
#include <iostream>

template <typename T>
T lerp(T a, T b, T t)
{
    return a + t * (b - a);
}

template <typename T>
void print_lerp(T a, T b, T t)
{
    std::cout << lerp(a, b, t) << '\n';
}
```

Any `.cpp` file that includes `math_utils.hpp` can call `lerp<float>`, `lerp<double>`, or any other floating-point specialisation without linker errors.

### Duplicate Instantiations Are Fine

Including the same header in multiple `.cpp` files means the compiler may instantiate `lerp<double>` in several translation units. The linker discards the duplicates — this is guaranteed by the One Definition Rule's exception for template instantiations. Compile times increase slightly, but correctness is maintained.

### The `extern template` Escape Hatch

If a specific instantiation is used in many translation units and compile time matters, you can explicitly instantiate it once in a `.cpp` file and declare it `extern` in the header:

```cpp
// header: suppress implicit instantiation
extern template double lerp<double>(double, double, double);

// one .cpp file: explicit instantiation
template double lerp<double>(double, double, double);
```

This is an optimisation, not a fix for the original problem — the definition still lives in the header.

### Key Takeaway

Default rule: **template definitions go in headers**. Reach for `extern template` only when profiling shows instantiation overhead is a real cost.

